WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.090 --> 00:00:01.600
RYAN GERMICK: Hello there.

00:00:01.600 --> 00:00:04.540
My name is Ryan and I lead
the Google Doodle team.

00:00:04.540 --> 00:00:07.430
And I'm here with a very
special guest at the

00:00:07.430 --> 00:00:10.027
Googleplex, Mr. Wayne White.

00:00:10.027 --> 00:00:11.428
Give it up.

00:00:11.428 --> 00:00:12.362
WAYNE WHITE: Thank you.

00:00:12.362 --> 00:00:13.612
Thank you.

00:00:16.780 --> 00:00:19.230
RYAN GERMICK: I'd been a fan of
Wayne's work before I even

00:00:19.230 --> 00:00:21.550
knew there was such a thing
as being a fan.

00:00:24.050 --> 00:00:26.690
His work entered into many
millions of American homes

00:00:26.690 --> 00:00:31.620
with the puppet design and other
assorted creativity for

00:00:31.620 --> 00:00:33.490
Pee Wee's Playhouse.

00:00:33.490 --> 00:00:36.670
It was years later when I first
saw one of your word

00:00:36.670 --> 00:00:42.190
paintings, the album cover for
Lambchop's "Nixon." And then a

00:00:42.190 --> 00:00:47.240
few years later after that I was
in a diner in LA, Fred 62,

00:00:47.240 --> 00:00:49.030
and I'm like, I know
this stuff.

00:00:49.030 --> 00:00:51.460
And then a little bit longer
after that when I saw a

00:00:51.460 --> 00:00:54.010
beautiful book that was recently
produced called "I

00:00:54.010 --> 00:00:55.510
Will Now Get the--"

00:00:55.510 --> 00:00:56.210
WAYNE WHITE: Maybe now.

00:00:56.210 --> 00:00:56.480
RYAN GERMICK: Maybe now.

00:00:56.480 --> 00:00:58.450
WAYNE WHITE: "Maybe Now I'll
Get the Respect I So Richly

00:00:58.450 --> 00:00:58.630
Deserve."

00:00:58.630 --> 00:00:59.490
RYAN GERMICK: Right.

00:00:59.490 --> 00:01:00.950
WAYNE WHITE: Ey.

00:01:00.950 --> 00:01:01.180
RYAN GERMICK: Yeah.

00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:04.099
I think today's the turning
point for that if I have

00:01:04.099 --> 00:01:05.060
anything to do with it.

00:01:05.060 --> 00:01:05.950
WAYNE WHITE: Finally.

00:01:05.950 --> 00:01:06.650
RYAN GERMICK: Finally.

00:01:06.650 --> 00:01:07.250
WAYNE WHITE: Today's the day.

00:01:07.250 --> 00:01:10.920
RYAN GERMICK: September
10, 2012.

00:01:10.920 --> 00:01:15.260
And it all came together in a
really wonderful movie that's

00:01:15.260 --> 00:01:17.410
coming out this fall.

00:01:17.410 --> 00:01:19.000
WAYNE WHITE: It's out now.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:19.740
RYAN GERMICK: Technically out.

00:01:19.740 --> 00:01:21.890
WAYNE WHITE: It premiered
September 7.

00:01:21.890 --> 00:01:24.840
And it's called "Beauty Is
Embarrassing." And it's the

00:01:24.840 --> 00:01:27.670
story of my life and times.

00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:27.860
RYAN GERMICK: Wonderful.

00:01:27.860 --> 00:01:30.830
And it's actually going to open
up in San Francisco and

00:01:30.830 --> 00:01:32.690
many other Bay Area locations
this weekend.

00:01:32.690 --> 00:01:33.170
WAYNE WHITE: Yes.

00:01:33.170 --> 00:01:35.680
I will be in the Bay
Area this weekend.

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:40.260
It's going to be in San
Francisco, Berkeley, San Jose,

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:41.740
and Santa Cruz.

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:44.640
You can go to
beautyisembarrassing.com for

00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:46.910
the theaters and times.

00:01:46.910 --> 00:01:48.330
I can't remember them all.

00:01:48.330 --> 00:01:50.225
But I take it a day at a time.

00:01:50.225 --> 00:01:51.040
RYAN GERMICK: Like sevenish.

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:51.760
7 PM, maybe.

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:52.700
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah, probably.

00:01:52.700 --> 00:01:53.170
7 or 8.

00:01:53.170 --> 00:01:53.695
RYAN GERMICK: Evening time.

00:01:53.695 --> 00:01:54.380
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah.

00:01:54.380 --> 00:01:55.350
You can call the--

00:01:55.350 --> 00:01:58.140
you can see the listings on
beautyisembarrassing.com and

00:01:58.140 --> 00:01:58.910
call your theaters.

00:01:58.910 --> 00:02:00.430
But I will be back up here.

00:02:00.430 --> 00:02:01.710
I love the Bay Area.

00:02:01.710 --> 00:02:04.060
Always have a great reception
when we come up here.

00:02:04.060 --> 00:02:05.450
RYAN GERMICK: Pandering
to the local crowd.

00:02:05.450 --> 00:02:06.630
WAYNE WHITE: I love you all.

00:02:06.630 --> 00:02:07.285
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:07.285 --> 00:02:08.000
RYAN GERMICK: And YouTube.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:09.050
You love YouTube.

00:02:09.050 --> 00:02:11.000
I imagine you love YouTube
and the people who

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:11.720
watch YouTube videos.

00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:12.170
WAYNE WHITE: Of course.

00:02:12.170 --> 00:02:12.470
Are you kidding?

00:02:12.470 --> 00:02:15.880
I'm on YouTube every day.

00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:17.930
RYAN GERMICK: Well, you have a
lot of new stuff going on.

00:02:17.930 --> 00:02:20.410
Always moving forward.

00:02:20.410 --> 00:02:21.870
If we could-- speaking
of moving forward.

00:02:21.870 --> 00:02:22.790
But it's not--

00:02:22.790 --> 00:02:23.720
you're not new to art.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:24.730
This is actually--

00:02:24.730 --> 00:02:26.290
this is a picture of your
great grandfather?

00:02:26.290 --> 00:02:26.650
WAYNE WHITE: No.

00:02:26.650 --> 00:02:27.040
It's me.

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:29.192
I've been doing these paintings
since 1878.

00:02:29.192 --> 00:02:30.680
RYAN GERMICK: Ah.

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:32.600
You aged very well.

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:35.050
WAYNE WHITE: I am a vampire.

00:02:35.050 --> 00:02:38.720
That's how I can do so much.

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:41.320
There's so much to talk about
just in this photograph.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:42.840
One is that your eyes
look really weird.

00:02:42.840 --> 00:02:44.140
Did you blink or something?

00:02:44.140 --> 00:02:45.545
WAYNE WHITE: No.

00:02:45.545 --> 00:02:47.570
Actually, this was
done by the great

00:02:47.570 --> 00:02:49.340
photographer Stephen Berkman.

00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:50.570
And this is his medium.

00:02:50.570 --> 00:02:55.370
He uses an original 1860s
glass-plate negative camera.

00:02:55.370 --> 00:02:56.830
It's called an ambrotype.

00:02:56.830 --> 00:02:59.590
He plays by all the 19th
century rules.

00:02:59.590 --> 00:03:00.860
Uses the same chemicals.

00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:02.880
He uses only natural light.

00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:05.850
And this particular kind of
film, the ambrotype, does not

00:03:05.850 --> 00:03:07.390
pick up blue.

00:03:07.390 --> 00:03:09.020
It does not pick
up light blues.

00:03:09.020 --> 00:03:10.800
Blue reads as white.

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:12.780
So that's why my eyes
have that creepy

00:03:12.780 --> 00:03:14.150
white glow to them.

00:03:14.150 --> 00:03:15.410
Because I have light
blue eyes.

00:03:15.410 --> 00:03:16.760
RYAN GERMICK: That's
a terrific answer.

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:17.770
Even if it's not true.

00:03:17.770 --> 00:03:19.380
WAYNE WHITE: It's true.

00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:20.000
It's true.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:20.520
RYAN GERMICK: I believe you.

00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:23.640
So I feel like we could talk for
the entire time just about

00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:25.430
this image, because there's all
these other images in it.

00:03:25.430 --> 00:03:28.810
But one thing I love, and I
think this kind of sums up in

00:03:28.810 --> 00:03:31.150
many ways your philosophy.

00:03:31.150 --> 00:03:32.610
I don't want you to spoil
all the good stuff.

00:03:32.610 --> 00:03:35.690
But the "Hoozy Thinky
Iz" image.

00:03:35.690 --> 00:03:36.760
Could you unpack that?

00:03:36.760 --> 00:03:38.310
Who do think you are?

00:03:38.310 --> 00:03:38.530
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah.

00:03:38.530 --> 00:03:42.500
That particular painting there,
"Hoozy Thinky Iz," that

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:43.830
is sort of--

00:03:43.830 --> 00:03:47.750
and I think a lot of my fellow
artists, maybe, can relate to

00:03:47.750 --> 00:03:50.330
this, and I talk about
it in the movie--

00:03:50.330 --> 00:03:53.170
it's a feeling of, especially
in our culture, who do you

00:03:53.170 --> 00:03:55.220
think you are getting up
there and making a

00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:56.840
spectacle of yourself?

00:03:56.840 --> 00:03:59.660
You must have a very high
opinion of yourself to go out

00:03:59.660 --> 00:04:03.150
there and push your so-called
"vision" on the world, or to

00:04:03.150 --> 00:04:06.530
be an "artiste," as people
like to call you.

00:04:06.530 --> 00:04:08.290
That's a subtle way of
putting you down.

00:04:08.290 --> 00:04:09.700
I hate that word.

00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:11.700
When so-- oh, here comes
the "artiste."

00:04:11.700 --> 00:04:14.190
RYAN GERMICK: I use it just to
sort of make fun of the word.

00:04:14.190 --> 00:04:14.830
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah.

00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:16.410
Double back on it.

00:04:16.410 --> 00:04:20.980
But this culture does not
respect or nurture artists.

00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:23.440
Maybe the San Francisco area,
there's pockets of

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:24.480
culture that does.

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:25.500
But on the whole--

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:27.900
especially, you can understand,
being a Midwest

00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:28.970
boy yourself.

00:04:28.970 --> 00:04:31.150
I'm a Southern boy.

00:04:31.150 --> 00:04:33.150
They do not respect and
nurture artists.

00:04:33.150 --> 00:04:37.650
And you grow up with this sort
of insecure feeling of, yeah,

00:04:37.650 --> 00:04:39.920
who do I think I am
for doing this?

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:43.560
Because everybody looks
askance at me.

00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:48.120
And it takes a certain amount
of ego to be an artist.

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:53.570
And our culture also sort of
looks down on the ego, as they

00:04:53.570 --> 00:04:55.930
should, because it can
get out of control.

00:04:55.930 --> 00:04:59.560
But the artist ego is such that
you start to question it.

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:02.070
Well, maybe I am a little out
of control with the ego.

00:05:02.070 --> 00:05:04.190
And who do I think I am?

00:05:04.190 --> 00:05:06.450
And it's just the natural
insecurity of the human

00:05:06.450 --> 00:05:09.430
condition to question
yourself that way.

00:05:09.430 --> 00:05:13.530
And it's amplified when you
take the artist's path.

00:05:13.530 --> 00:05:16.350
And it's amplified also
when you see people

00:05:16.350 --> 00:05:17.590
better than you are.

00:05:17.590 --> 00:05:19.660
Well, who do I think I am?

00:05:19.660 --> 00:05:21.890
This guy's ten times
better than me.

00:05:21.890 --> 00:05:22.950
I'm humbled by it.

00:05:22.950 --> 00:05:24.970
RYAN GERMICK: You mentioned
respect for artists.

00:05:24.970 --> 00:05:27.380
That's a good lead-in to-- we
have another slide, if you

00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:28.930
want to show.

00:05:28.930 --> 00:05:30.400
Talk a little bit about
this painting.

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:35.670
WAYNE WHITE: This is called
"Picasso's Ass Falling Off."

00:05:35.670 --> 00:05:39.620
Now, this is a secret that I've
never revealed when I've

00:05:39.620 --> 00:05:41.920
said this title or showed
this painting.

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:45.800
I first heard the expression
"ass falling off" from the

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:47.610
artist James Rosenquist.

00:05:47.610 --> 00:05:48.620
RYAN GERMICK: Oh, yeah.

00:05:48.620 --> 00:05:49.970
He used to be a billboard
painter.

00:05:49.970 --> 00:05:51.380
Another commercial artist
turned fine artist.

00:05:51.380 --> 00:05:51.810
WAYNE WHITE: Yes.

00:05:51.810 --> 00:05:55.000
He's a very famous pop artist.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:56.850
Very influential
in the culture.

00:05:56.850 --> 00:05:59.640
And I happened to meet him at
a party once that I went to

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:03.140
with the great Red Grooms, who
I also worked for at one time

00:06:03.140 --> 00:06:04.140
in New York City.

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:06.950
And I was like this 24-year-old
kid straight out

00:06:06.950 --> 00:06:09.670
of Tennessee in this room full
of these superstars of

00:06:09.670 --> 00:06:10.820
American art.

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:13.220
And Rosenquist was holding
court about his days as a

00:06:13.220 --> 00:06:14.270
billboard painter.

00:06:14.270 --> 00:06:17.280
This is kind of off topic, but--
he goes, yeah, and I

00:06:17.280 --> 00:06:18.440
went to the boss that day.

00:06:18.440 --> 00:06:21.380
I said, boss, I feel like my
ass is going to fall off.

00:06:21.380 --> 00:06:23.370
And I thought about that
term for years.

00:06:23.370 --> 00:06:25.390
And I associated it with
art and artists.

00:06:25.390 --> 00:06:29.080
And that inspired me to have
Picasso's ass falling off.

00:06:29.080 --> 00:06:31.075
And this is just sort
of a jab at the king

00:06:31.075 --> 00:06:34.460
of art, Pablo Picasso.

00:06:34.460 --> 00:06:37.380
I mean, that's a guy that
anybody who's put pencil to

00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:39.830
paper or tried to make a
painting, that's one guy you

00:06:39.830 --> 00:06:41.830
have to get around or
over or through.

00:06:41.830 --> 00:06:45.060
You have to pass through Picasso
Land sooner or later

00:06:45.060 --> 00:06:46.370
if you're an artist.

00:06:46.370 --> 00:06:49.900
And this is just kind of like
throwing darts at the king.

00:06:53.070 --> 00:06:54.110
I love Picasso.

00:06:54.110 --> 00:06:55.110
All artists do.

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:56.590
You can't help but.

00:06:56.590 --> 00:06:57.430
You have to pay respect.

00:06:57.430 --> 00:07:02.800
But at the same time, this
reflects one of my abiding

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:06.490
passions in art, is to bring
humor into fine art.

00:07:06.490 --> 00:07:09.550
And to poke pins in
pretensions, to

00:07:09.550 --> 00:07:11.620
rail against the king.

00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:13.030
That's a very American thing.

00:07:13.030 --> 00:07:14.450
We hate kings.

00:07:14.450 --> 00:07:16.690
That's why this culture--
that's why

00:07:16.690 --> 00:07:18.090
this country was started.

00:07:18.090 --> 00:07:19.670
To rail against monarchy.

00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:22.330
To break down class systems.

00:07:22.330 --> 00:07:25.210
And that's a big part of
what humor does, is

00:07:25.210 --> 00:07:26.770
to break down walls.

00:07:26.770 --> 00:07:30.170
And to laugh at class
distinctions and everything.

00:07:30.170 --> 00:07:32.780
And to bring everything to
a level playing field.

00:07:32.780 --> 00:07:35.300
We're all hairless apes.

00:07:35.300 --> 00:07:39.400
RYAN GERMICK: Well, some
more than others.

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:43.160
So what is it about art
that is so afraid of

00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:45.020
humor, do you think?

00:07:45.020 --> 00:07:47.525
Is that universal, or do you
think it's historical?

00:07:47.525 --> 00:07:50.930
WAYNE WHITE: It's not
necessarily universal.

00:07:50.930 --> 00:07:55.420
First of all, I consider humor
an elevated form of

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:56.140
consciousness.

00:07:56.140 --> 00:07:58.830
I think it's one of the most
sacred, valuable qualities we

00:07:58.830 --> 00:08:00.350
have as human beings.

00:08:00.350 --> 00:08:04.470
And so why shouldn't it be
worthy of the canon of art?

00:08:04.470 --> 00:08:08.700
Why shouldn't it be in
museums and whatnot?

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:12.080
I consider stand-up comics,
especially people like Richard

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:16.590
Pryor, Lenny Bruce, George
Carlin to be fine artists.

00:08:16.590 --> 00:08:20.460
It's one of the finest
art forms there is.

00:08:20.460 --> 00:08:24.710
But you know, art is
famously humorless.

00:08:24.710 --> 00:08:27.780
Especially critics, curators.

00:08:27.780 --> 00:08:31.440
A certain type of class
consciousness invades art.

00:08:31.440 --> 00:08:34.600
People go to the best schools,
Ivy League schools.

00:08:34.600 --> 00:08:38.573
Ivy League people control the
art world through criticism

00:08:38.573 --> 00:08:41.230
and through curatorship.

00:08:41.230 --> 00:08:43.599
And through the fast track that
they're on by going to

00:08:43.599 --> 00:08:45.240
these moneyed schools.

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:48.850
Moneyed schools do not want
to talk about humor.

00:08:48.850 --> 00:08:51.210
Humor is considered lightweight
and low.

00:08:51.210 --> 00:08:54.060
It's considered an
entertainment.

00:08:54.060 --> 00:08:57.490
And not worthy of serious
contemplation.

00:08:57.490 --> 00:08:59.110
RYAN GERMICK: Did you ever
read the book "Ways of

00:08:59.110 --> 00:09:00.910
Seeing," by John Berger?

00:09:00.910 --> 00:09:02.120
WAYNE WHITE: Yes.

00:09:02.120 --> 00:09:03.290
I've read all--

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:04.250
that's another thing.

00:09:04.250 --> 00:09:05.040
RYAN GERMICK: You've
read every book?

00:09:05.040 --> 00:09:07.340
WAYNE WHITE: I've read
every book there is.

00:09:07.340 --> 00:09:08.776
No, I--

00:09:08.776 --> 00:09:10.590
RYAN GERMICK: Makes it easier
to discuss with

00:09:10.590 --> 00:09:11.230
you, because I--

00:09:11.230 --> 00:09:14.070
WAYNE WHITE: I come from
this working class,

00:09:14.070 --> 00:09:17.310
chip-on-my-shoulder kind
of attitude, but

00:09:17.310 --> 00:09:18.700
I've run the gamut.

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:21.830
I've read Berger, Clement
Greenberg, all the criticisms.

00:09:21.830 --> 00:09:22.880
I love fine art.

00:09:22.880 --> 00:09:24.370
I love the higher
forms of art.

00:09:24.370 --> 00:09:25.520
I love seriousness.

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:28.100
I love drama.

00:09:28.100 --> 00:09:30.280
I love the challenges
of difficult art.

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:33.140
I'm not discounting any of it,
I'm just saying there's room

00:09:33.140 --> 00:09:34.630
for other forms of it.

00:09:34.630 --> 00:09:35.790
RYAN GERMICK: Yeah.

00:09:35.790 --> 00:09:36.900
Well, the thing that
blew my mind.

00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:39.230
I was in high school, I think,
when an art teacher gave that

00:09:39.230 --> 00:09:40.120
book to me.

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:43.220
And this is less about humor
but more about the value of

00:09:43.220 --> 00:09:45.480
maybe commercial art, was he--

00:09:45.480 --> 00:09:47.740
and I totally maybe misread
this, so someone could go back

00:09:47.740 --> 00:09:50.870
and look this up, and this was
like 15, 16 years ago.

00:09:50.870 --> 00:09:54.700
But I remember him talking about
fine art having this

00:09:54.700 --> 00:09:58.380
inherent classicism because it's
an art object owned by

00:09:58.380 --> 00:09:59.520
one person.

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:02.490
And with that rarity and
scarcity, it becomes a

00:10:02.490 --> 00:10:05.600
situation of supply and demand
and the rich person gets it.

00:10:05.600 --> 00:10:08.040
And so I think it's
interesting--

00:10:08.040 --> 00:10:11.160
you've had multi-faceted career
we talked about it a

00:10:11.160 --> 00:10:11.500
little bit.

00:10:11.500 --> 00:10:16.300
But art that is not exclusive to
one person but can still be

00:10:16.300 --> 00:10:18.310
art seems to threaten that

00:10:18.310 --> 00:10:20.670
long-established supply and demand.

00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:23.040
WAYNE WHITE: And Berger, if
I'm not mistaken was a

00:10:23.040 --> 00:10:25.620
communist , or at least
a socialist.

00:10:25.620 --> 00:10:26.120
He was.

00:10:26.120 --> 00:10:27.870
RYAN GERMICK: There seemed
to be implications, yeah.

00:10:27.870 --> 00:10:29.430
WAYNE WHITE: He was a
radical socialist.

00:10:29.430 --> 00:10:34.190
And he believed in bringing up
the thorny problem of class

00:10:34.190 --> 00:10:35.530
within the art world.

00:10:35.530 --> 00:10:38.400
And that's a dirty secret of
the art world, is it's very

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:39.950
much ruled by money.

00:10:39.950 --> 00:10:41.920
And the moneyed class.

00:10:41.920 --> 00:10:44.260
And I forgot my direction.

00:10:44.260 --> 00:10:46.430
RYAN GERMICK: Can I tell you
a story why I chose in art

00:10:46.430 --> 00:10:49.150
school not to go into fine
art but to go into

00:10:49.150 --> 00:10:50.080
illustration as a major?

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:50.410
WAYNE WHITE: Sure.

00:10:50.410 --> 00:10:51.180
Please do.

00:10:51.180 --> 00:10:52.520
RYAN GERMICK: So I was in--

00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:54.620
I feel like I should be
looking at the camera.

00:10:54.620 --> 00:10:57.990
This is a serious moment.

00:10:57.990 --> 00:11:02.240
I was 18 years old.

00:11:02.240 --> 00:11:03.540
I went to Parsons School
of Design.

00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:05.600
And the fine arts department
has wonderful

00:11:05.600 --> 00:11:07.100
students and teachers.

00:11:07.100 --> 00:11:09.020
But when I went to the
information session, when

00:11:09.020 --> 00:11:11.430
they're trying to get you to
pick a major, they had free

00:11:11.430 --> 00:11:15.790
pizza, which was a
big draw for me.

00:11:15.790 --> 00:11:16.970
Poor student and whatnot.

00:11:16.970 --> 00:11:21.670
And they were going on and on
about how wonderful their

00:11:21.670 --> 00:11:22.550
facilities were.

00:11:22.550 --> 00:11:26.730
That they had state of the art--
they had studio space

00:11:26.730 --> 00:11:30.360
right in Manhattan and access to
the galleries and museums.

00:11:30.360 --> 00:11:32.570
And for people that were into
sculpture, they had just

00:11:32.570 --> 00:11:34.350
bought a plasma cutter.

00:11:34.350 --> 00:11:38.670
And meanwhile, I'm trying to
get pizza off of the pie.

00:11:38.670 --> 00:11:40.630
I'm trying to pull this slice of
pizza and kind of trying to

00:11:40.630 --> 00:11:43.900
keep it cool, but the smart alec
in me couldn't help but

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:45.760
blurt out, could I
use the plasma

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:48.005
cutter to get this pizza?

00:11:48.005 --> 00:11:49.700
WAYNE WHITE: And that went
over like a led balloon?

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:51.190
RYAN GERMICK: Totally
crickets.

00:11:51.190 --> 00:11:53.140
And then I was like, I don't
need these guys.

00:11:53.140 --> 00:11:53.590
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah.

00:11:53.590 --> 00:11:55.110
There you go.

00:11:55.110 --> 00:11:55.550
I know.

00:11:55.550 --> 00:11:59.730
It's like, humor is one of my
acid tests for human beings.

00:11:59.730 --> 00:12:01.260
You know what I mean?

00:12:01.260 --> 00:12:04.300
If somebody doesn't have a sense
of humor, it's over.

00:12:04.300 --> 00:12:06.890
I can't relate to them.

00:12:06.890 --> 00:12:08.460
I value humor.

00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:11.885
And paradoxically, you can't
analyze humor and put it on

00:12:11.885 --> 00:12:14.650
too high an elevation
or it kills it.

00:12:14.650 --> 00:12:18.500
It's this precious little flower
that has to grow in a

00:12:18.500 --> 00:12:21.220
certain way, but why can't
it grow in a museum?

00:12:21.220 --> 00:12:26.290
Why can't it be considered
worthy of--

00:12:26.290 --> 00:12:28.120
I think it has depth.

00:12:28.120 --> 00:12:28.870
I do.

00:12:28.870 --> 00:12:31.000
As much depth as any
other form of art.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:31.770
RYAN GERMICK: I agree
with you.

00:12:31.770 --> 00:12:34.580
WAYNE WHITE: The best humor has
levels of sadness and all

00:12:34.580 --> 00:12:37.151
the emotions.

00:12:37.151 --> 00:12:37.630
RYAN GERMICK: Right on.

00:12:37.630 --> 00:12:39.480
Can I get the next slide?

00:12:39.480 --> 00:12:42.110
So this is somewhat of a
good transition here.

00:12:42.110 --> 00:12:45.180
So you grew up in Tennessee,
as you mentioned.

00:12:45.180 --> 00:12:45.610
WAYNE WHITE: Yes.

00:12:45.610 --> 00:12:46.932
Chattanooga, Tennessee.

00:12:46.932 --> 00:12:48.420
RYAN GERMICK: Chattanooga.

00:12:48.420 --> 00:12:50.640
And then you moved
to New York.

00:12:50.640 --> 00:12:51.200
Kind of high-tailed--

00:12:51.200 --> 00:12:52.730
you went to college
in Tennessee.

00:12:52.730 --> 00:12:55.260
WAYNE WHITE: I had four years
of undergraduate school at a

00:12:55.260 --> 00:12:58.360
state university, Middle
Tennessee State University.

00:12:58.360 --> 00:13:01.860
I drifted around Nashville,
Tennessee for a half year

00:13:01.860 --> 00:13:03.090
after I graduated.

00:13:03.090 --> 00:13:06.140
I saw a magazine called "Raw
Magazine" put out by Art

00:13:06.140 --> 00:13:08.170
Spiegelman in 1981.

00:13:08.170 --> 00:13:10.920
And that inspired me to move to
New York, because I saw in

00:13:10.920 --> 00:13:13.620
that magazine, and his spirit,
and the artists in that

00:13:13.620 --> 00:13:16.310
magazine, the birth of a
new world, the birth

00:13:16.310 --> 00:13:17.390
of a new art form.

00:13:17.390 --> 00:13:18.450
And I was right.

00:13:18.450 --> 00:13:22.480
That magazine and that scene in
the early '80s in New York

00:13:22.480 --> 00:13:26.210
is becoming true today in the
Renaissance of graphic novels.

00:13:26.210 --> 00:13:27.270
Go to any comic book store.

00:13:27.270 --> 00:13:27.960
RYAN GERMICK: Yeah,
it's everywhere.

00:13:27.960 --> 00:13:29.960
WAYNE WHITE: And it all started
back then, at least in

00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:33.400
America, in the early '80s in
New York City down on Greene

00:13:33.400 --> 00:13:36.100
Street in Soho in Art
Spiegelman's studio.

00:13:36.100 --> 00:13:39.280
RYAN GERMICK: When you were in
Middle Tennessee University,

00:13:39.280 --> 00:13:41.160
you also found a community
of folks.

00:13:41.160 --> 00:13:44.610
WAYNE WHITE: I was lucky enough,
coincidentally, to run

00:13:44.610 --> 00:13:50.350
into fellow weirdo oddballs from
small towns of the South.

00:13:50.350 --> 00:13:53.530
And we were all dying to
validate each other.

00:13:53.530 --> 00:13:56.010
We had all come from a
suppressed background.

00:13:56.010 --> 00:13:58.750
We had all been made to
feel like outsiders.

00:13:58.750 --> 00:14:02.240
And suddenly, we were together
and reinforcing each other.

00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:07.320
And I always say, your fellow
students are just as

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:09.910
important, or maybe more
important, to your education

00:14:09.910 --> 00:14:11.970
than your teachers are.

00:14:11.970 --> 00:14:18.680
I think you can learn as much
from your peers as you can

00:14:18.680 --> 00:14:22.700
from your instructors and your
so-called authority figures.

00:14:22.700 --> 00:14:26.120
And that's where I first came
out of my shell and first

00:14:26.120 --> 00:14:28.460
learned about art
and art history.

00:14:28.460 --> 00:14:32.440
And just as art as a lifestyle,
as something that

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:35.520
can bleed out of the classroom,
into the streets,

00:14:35.520 --> 00:14:39.420
become a part of your
everyday life.

00:14:39.420 --> 00:14:40.950
RYAN GERMICK: So it seems
clear to me--

00:14:40.950 --> 00:14:43.080
and I had a similar experience
when I went to--

00:14:43.080 --> 00:14:45.070
feel free to check your
email or whatever.

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:47.700
We can cut this out.

00:14:47.700 --> 00:14:50.940
So it seems clear to me that
that community helped as a

00:14:50.940 --> 00:14:52.140
launching pad.

00:14:52.140 --> 00:14:53.800
And I'm sure many of the
creative people in the

00:14:53.800 --> 00:14:57.330
audience and watching this on
YouTube or whatever have had

00:14:57.330 --> 00:14:57.800
that experience.

00:14:57.800 --> 00:15:02.500
Do you feel like now in today's
very connected world--

00:15:02.500 --> 00:15:06.170
how do you feel technology is
helping people find weirdos

00:15:06.170 --> 00:15:08.980
and communities that they feel
accepted and validated by?

00:15:08.980 --> 00:15:10.160
WAYNE WHITE: I think
it's helping a lot.

00:15:10.160 --> 00:15:12.100
I think it's helping connect
people in ways

00:15:12.100 --> 00:15:13.570
that are really positive.

00:15:13.570 --> 00:15:16.990
I'm not one of those guys that
rues the day before computers.

00:15:16.990 --> 00:15:20.280
I'm not one of those guys that
believes in a golden age or

00:15:20.280 --> 00:15:22.350
the good old days.

00:15:22.350 --> 00:15:24.980
Young people, please, believe
this for sure.

00:15:24.980 --> 00:15:26.430
There's no good old days.

00:15:26.430 --> 00:15:28.650
There's no golden age that
you missed out on.

00:15:28.650 --> 00:15:30.450
You're not missing
out on anything.

00:15:30.450 --> 00:15:32.530
You're alive right now.

00:15:32.530 --> 00:15:33.840
Now's your golden age.

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:36.480
Don't listen to some old fart
tell you it used to be better.

00:15:36.480 --> 00:15:38.530
Because it wasn't.

00:15:38.530 --> 00:15:41.300
It wasn't better.

00:15:41.300 --> 00:15:44.570
What is important is, make
this your golden age.

00:15:44.570 --> 00:15:47.460
And when you get to be my age,
don't sit around saying, boy,

00:15:47.460 --> 00:15:50.480
back in the Google days, back
when Google first started--

00:15:50.480 --> 00:15:51.970
don't do that.

00:15:51.970 --> 00:15:55.730
Please, remember this day
when I'm telling you.

00:15:55.730 --> 00:15:57.370
Don't turn into one
of those people.

00:15:57.370 --> 00:15:58.240
Look forward.

00:15:58.240 --> 00:15:59.685
Keep believing in the future.

00:15:59.685 --> 00:16:00.935
And change.

00:16:03.480 --> 00:16:04.380
RYAN GERMICK: Next.

00:16:04.380 --> 00:16:06.710
So I want to go a
little bit back.

00:16:06.710 --> 00:16:08.990
This is a still from
the movie.

00:16:08.990 --> 00:16:11.200
It's one of my favorite
sections.

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:13.090
There's a lot of talk in the
movie about your upbringing.

00:16:13.090 --> 00:16:15.780
And about your relationship with
both your family, like

00:16:15.780 --> 00:16:18.230
your parents, but then your new
family, which is really

00:16:18.230 --> 00:16:19.820
terrific, which we'll talk
about in a second.

00:16:19.820 --> 00:16:22.230
But it just goes over--
you have a line in the

00:16:22.230 --> 00:16:23.820
movie that I love.

00:16:23.820 --> 00:16:26.200
And this is your sister
about to spank you.

00:16:26.200 --> 00:16:27.155
WAYNE WHITE: Yes.

00:16:27.155 --> 00:16:30.090
RYAN GERMICK: And you said
something like your sister was

00:16:30.090 --> 00:16:35.090
the person who told you you were
going to die one day and

00:16:35.090 --> 00:16:36.590
made sure you understood
the concept.

00:16:36.590 --> 00:16:38.570
WAYNE WHITE: Yes.

00:16:38.570 --> 00:16:39.560
RYAN GERMICK: I love
that because--

00:16:39.560 --> 00:16:40.710
WAYNE WHITE: That's what I'm--

00:16:40.710 --> 00:16:43.830
that's what the V.O. is right
when this scene is happening.

00:16:43.830 --> 00:16:47.620
I said, and my sister was
the first bad-ass.

00:16:47.620 --> 00:16:51.270
She was the one that told me I
was going to die one day and

00:16:51.270 --> 00:16:54.730
made sure I was crystal
clear on the concept.

00:16:54.730 --> 00:16:56.820
RYAN GERMICK: So we chatted
a little bit earlier and--

00:16:56.820 --> 00:16:57.470
WAYNE WHITE: And it's true.

00:16:57.470 --> 00:16:59.000
RYAN GERMICK: --you were talking
about the old fogies

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:00.990
talking about the good old days,
and how that relates to

00:17:00.990 --> 00:17:01.990
a fear of death.

00:17:01.990 --> 00:17:02.230
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah.

00:17:02.230 --> 00:17:02.860
RYAN GERMICK: In a sense.

00:17:02.860 --> 00:17:06.050
I'm kind of curious how-- if you
would unpack that for me.

00:17:06.050 --> 00:17:09.640
And also, your sister-- you're
just a youngin here.

00:17:09.640 --> 00:17:11.089
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah, I'm like
four years old there.

00:17:11.089 --> 00:17:12.290
RYAN GERMICK: Yeah, and she's
letting-- you know, I'm

00:17:12.290 --> 00:17:15.849
imagining at an early age,
this idea of you're an

00:17:15.849 --> 00:17:18.069
infallible mortal is a pretty
heavy thing to learn.

00:17:18.069 --> 00:17:20.470
But it seems like you take that
lesson to heart today.

00:17:20.470 --> 00:17:23.270
WAYNE WHITE: You know what, I
can trace my first existential

00:17:23.270 --> 00:17:26.470
crisis to that day when my
sister very patiently

00:17:26.470 --> 00:17:28.119
explained to me that we
were all going to be

00:17:28.119 --> 00:17:29.370
dead forever one day.

00:17:29.370 --> 00:17:34.260
And I remember the feeling when
it first pierced me, that

00:17:34.260 --> 00:17:37.160
that was a realization.

00:17:37.160 --> 00:17:40.020
And I've had anxiety attacks
my whole life about that.

00:17:40.020 --> 00:17:43.310
And I think a lot of us have
the same feelings.

00:17:43.310 --> 00:17:46.490
I think a lot of us, the
mortality thing creeps up on

00:17:46.490 --> 00:17:49.910
you when you least expect it,
and you are short of breath.

00:17:49.910 --> 00:17:55.280
And you suddenly realize, wow,
this is a limited engagement

00:17:55.280 --> 00:17:56.195
we're all in.

00:17:56.195 --> 00:18:00.750
And I think that's a painful
realization, but I think it's

00:18:00.750 --> 00:18:04.020
a realization that most
artists share.

00:18:04.020 --> 00:18:06.570
That's one of the motivators,
that's one of the engines of

00:18:06.570 --> 00:18:08.760
art, is knowing that
this is a limited

00:18:08.760 --> 00:18:11.280
engagement, that we're here.

00:18:11.280 --> 00:18:13.130
Time is precious.

00:18:13.130 --> 00:18:16.180
And we've got to do the
best we can with it.

00:18:16.180 --> 00:18:19.350
I think that one of the great
things about artists, is they

00:18:19.350 --> 00:18:21.160
take advantage of that time.

00:18:21.160 --> 00:18:26.850
I think we all have this acute
realization that we're mortal.

00:18:26.850 --> 00:18:30.380
And I think art is sort
of, as they say--

00:18:30.380 --> 00:18:32.960
the academic term
is memento mori.

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:35.200
That's one of the big
themes of art.

00:18:35.200 --> 00:18:38.710
It's been there ever
since art began.

00:18:38.710 --> 00:18:42.580
Still lives from the
golden age--

00:18:42.580 --> 00:18:43.970
here I go, golden age.

00:18:43.970 --> 00:18:44.690
Still lives--

00:18:44.690 --> 00:18:46.400
RYAN GERMICK: Well, as a
vampire, you have a much wider

00:18:46.400 --> 00:18:47.680
perspective.

00:18:47.680 --> 00:18:50.280
WAYNE WHITE: Still lives from
the Renaissance on are

00:18:50.280 --> 00:18:51.580
symbolic of death.

00:18:51.580 --> 00:18:52.840
They're called memento mori.

00:18:52.840 --> 00:18:54.165
Fruit, flowers--

00:18:57.110 --> 00:19:02.270
those are subtle symbols of
death, and reminding us of the

00:19:02.270 --> 00:19:03.920
mortal coil.

00:19:03.920 --> 00:19:08.300
So the realization of mortality
is built into art.

00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:11.470
And that's what gives it its
poignancy and power.

00:19:11.470 --> 00:19:13.440
And that's what gives
humor its power.

00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:18.420
Humor is often a reaction
against a--

00:19:18.420 --> 00:19:18.900
RYAN GERMICK: Release
against fear.

00:19:18.900 --> 00:19:20.970
WAYNE WHITE: --a release
against fear.

00:19:20.970 --> 00:19:23.900
Facing that horrible truth.

00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:27.060
So that's why humor should be
right up there, along with the

00:19:27.060 --> 00:19:28.430
old masters and stuff.

00:19:28.430 --> 00:19:30.310
Because that's what
an artist does.

00:19:30.310 --> 00:19:34.660
He defies death, yet he also
comes to terms with it.

00:19:34.660 --> 00:19:38.360
And that's why art is in
the spiritual realm.

00:19:38.360 --> 00:19:39.130
RYAN GERMICK: Do you want to--

00:19:39.130 --> 00:19:40.360
I come from a big family.

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:41.280
I'm the middle of five kids.

00:19:41.280 --> 00:19:42.780
And I know that my siblings
did a lot to

00:19:42.780 --> 00:19:43.805
shape me as a person.

00:19:43.805 --> 00:19:46.370
And as a creative person.

00:19:46.370 --> 00:19:47.720
What about you?

00:19:47.720 --> 00:19:49.700
From what I gather, it doesn't
seem like your sister was

00:19:49.700 --> 00:19:52.440
particularly creative, but your
mom was pretty creative.

00:19:52.440 --> 00:19:54.580
WAYNE WHITE: My mother was
the first artist, so to

00:19:54.580 --> 00:19:55.570
speak, in my life.

00:19:55.570 --> 00:19:56.820
The first aesthete.

00:19:58.970 --> 00:20:01.870
Mind you, I grew
up in a very--

00:20:01.870 --> 00:20:08.120
it was the '60s in the South,
which was the '50s, really.

00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:09.150
RYAN GERMICK: But it's
still 10 years above

00:20:09.150 --> 00:20:10.055
the Midwest, I think.

00:20:10.055 --> 00:20:11.420
It's still like the
future for us.

00:20:11.420 --> 00:20:14.150
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah, I mean, I
grew up in a blue collar

00:20:14.150 --> 00:20:14.920
environment.

00:20:14.920 --> 00:20:17.620
All my father's friends, my
father himself, they all work

00:20:17.620 --> 00:20:19.350
at DuPont nylon factory.

00:20:19.350 --> 00:20:21.000
There wasn't an artist
in sight.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:22.410
There wasn't a gallery
in sight.

00:20:22.410 --> 00:20:24.110
There wasn't a museum.

00:20:24.110 --> 00:20:28.440
And so the first artist in that
kind of environment was

00:20:28.440 --> 00:20:31.850
my mother, because she
loved antiques.

00:20:31.850 --> 00:20:33.500
She loved to decorate.

00:20:33.500 --> 00:20:35.370
She took me to antique
stores all the time.

00:20:35.370 --> 00:20:37.970
She admired objects
for their beauty.

00:20:37.970 --> 00:20:40.400
And her sense of interior
decorating--

00:20:40.400 --> 00:20:43.180
she redecorated the house
like every month.

00:20:43.180 --> 00:20:44.770
So she was a designer.

00:20:44.770 --> 00:20:48.920
And she was my first idea of
someone who could enjoy the

00:20:48.920 --> 00:20:53.010
visual, and enjoy expressing
the visual.

00:20:53.010 --> 00:20:55.110
RYAN GERMICK: Wanna hit
the next slide?

00:20:55.110 --> 00:20:57.700
So this a shot of
your family now.

