00:23:10.930 --> 00:23:12.660
RYAN GERMICK: Well, the
third is that--

00:23:12.660 --> 00:23:13.690
I want to talk a bit
about "Pee Wee."

00:23:13.690 --> 00:23:15.800
WAYNE WHITE: Sure.

00:23:15.800 --> 00:23:20.280
RYAN GERMICK: So "Pee
Wee" was a special

00:23:20.280 --> 00:23:21.495
thing in American culture.

00:23:21.495 --> 00:23:22.520
WAYNE WHITE: It sure was.

00:23:22.520 --> 00:23:25.130
RYAN GERMICK: It was just
so much creativity and

00:23:25.130 --> 00:23:26.580
originality.

00:23:26.580 --> 00:23:27.830
And it was a huge hit.

00:23:27.830 --> 00:23:28.170
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah.

00:23:28.170 --> 00:23:31.690
RYAN GERMICK: I mean, it was
a big deal in my childhood.

00:23:31.690 --> 00:23:35.520
And just basically, as a weird
kid in the Midwest, it felt

00:23:35.520 --> 00:23:37.810
like a breath of fresh air.

00:23:37.810 --> 00:23:40.570
And I think Matt Groening said
it best, when he said--he was

00:23:40.570 --> 00:23:43.900
referring to "Pee Wee" in the
trailer when he said, if this

00:23:43.900 --> 00:23:45.570
could make it, there's
hope for us all.

00:23:45.570 --> 00:23:46.370
WAYNE WHITE: Yes.

00:23:46.370 --> 00:23:47.590
RYAN GERMICK: And that's what
I took away from the movie,

00:23:47.590 --> 00:23:50.540
but in particular from "Pee
Wee." That's just one of these

00:23:50.540 --> 00:23:53.060
moments of, you know,
the good guys won.

00:23:53.060 --> 00:23:54.440
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah.

00:23:54.440 --> 00:23:56.680
RYAN GERMICK: How did you
go from your New York

00:23:56.680 --> 00:23:58.340
cartooning into that?

00:23:58.340 --> 00:24:00.730
And I just want to hear
all about it.

00:24:00.730 --> 00:24:03.400
WAYNE WHITE: Well, like I said,
I moved to New York to

00:24:03.400 --> 00:24:04.280
be a cartoonist.

00:24:04.280 --> 00:24:07.560
But at the same time, I'd been
doing these crazy, wacky

00:24:07.560 --> 00:24:09.200
puppet shows on my own.

00:24:09.200 --> 00:24:11.930
Just these do-it-yourself
homemade productions.

00:24:11.930 --> 00:24:16.820
I started those back in
Tennessee at the university.

00:24:16.820 --> 00:24:20.020
When punk rock first hit, I
couldn't play a guitar, so I

00:24:20.020 --> 00:24:22.260
picked up a puppet instead.

00:24:22.260 --> 00:24:24.280
And I did these things,
I called them

00:24:24.280 --> 00:24:25.700
punk rock puppet shows.

00:24:25.700 --> 00:24:31.250
The first one was called "Punk
and Juicy." And the puppets

00:24:31.250 --> 00:24:33.330
bled fountains of blood.

00:24:33.330 --> 00:24:35.450
We would throw bowls
of Cheerios

00:24:35.450 --> 00:24:36.790
and milk at the audience.

00:24:36.790 --> 00:24:38.550
We'd set fire to the stage.

00:24:38.550 --> 00:24:41.030
We'd come out and choke members
of the audience and

00:24:41.030 --> 00:24:42.460
provoke fights.

00:24:42.460 --> 00:24:44.420
It was very confrontational.

00:24:44.420 --> 00:24:46.750
It was kind of anti-puppet.

00:24:46.750 --> 00:24:50.580
It was the era of Andy Kaufman
and Mr. Bill and, like

00:24:50.580 --> 00:24:51.605
I said, punk rock.

00:24:51.605 --> 00:24:54.610
It was all about deconstruction
and

00:24:54.610 --> 00:24:57.070
destruction, you know?

00:24:57.070 --> 00:25:00.130
It was about kicking down the
old conventions and finding

00:25:00.130 --> 00:25:02.970
something new, taking apart
the idea of show business,

00:25:02.970 --> 00:25:04.330
confronting the audience.

00:25:04.330 --> 00:25:06.340
Which is not a new
idea at all.

00:25:06.340 --> 00:25:09.120
It was also my idea
of art history.

00:25:09.120 --> 00:25:13.160
I thought of myself as a Dadaist
in the tradition of

00:25:13.160 --> 00:25:17.420
Hugo Ball and all those guys
that came out of the aftermath

00:25:17.420 --> 00:25:18.780
of World War I.

00:25:18.780 --> 00:25:20.500
RYAN GERMICK: Sounds like the
perfect set for children's

00:25:20.500 --> 00:25:20.980
television.

00:25:20.980 --> 00:25:22.880
WAYNE WHITE: Perfect.

00:25:22.880 --> 00:25:24.110
Right up kids' alley.

00:25:24.110 --> 00:25:27.300
Everybody wants to know about a
dystopian future, you know?

00:25:27.300 --> 00:25:28.110
RYAN GERMICK: Right.

00:25:28.110 --> 00:25:28.780
Right.

00:25:28.780 --> 00:25:30.540
What was that transition?

00:25:30.540 --> 00:25:32.910
Who was the visionary that
pulled all of you crazies in?

00:25:32.910 --> 00:25:34.330
WAYNE WHITE: Well, I kept
doing those puppet

00:25:34.330 --> 00:25:36.320
shows on the side.

00:25:36.320 --> 00:25:38.230
And everybody thought I
was crazy to do it.

00:25:38.230 --> 00:25:41.890
And lo and behold, that puppet
show experience got me the job

00:25:41.890 --> 00:25:43.450
on "Pee Wee's Playhouse."

00:25:43.450 --> 00:25:47.620
And that's another lesson I
impart to young artists, or

00:25:47.620 --> 00:25:49.530
people who want to
be an artist.

00:25:49.530 --> 00:25:51.570
Everybody thought I was
nuts to do that, to do

00:25:51.570 --> 00:25:52.590
those puppet shows.

00:25:52.590 --> 00:25:55.150
They kept trying to give me all
this common sense advice--

00:25:55.150 --> 00:25:56.370
Wayne, focus.

00:25:56.370 --> 00:25:58.180
Be a graphic artist.

00:25:58.180 --> 00:25:59.080
Be an Illustrator.

00:25:59.080 --> 00:26:00.190
Go where the money is.

00:26:00.190 --> 00:26:01.410
Use your sense.

00:26:01.410 --> 00:26:03.870
Quit playing with dolls
all the time.

00:26:03.870 --> 00:26:07.950
But lo and behold, what
everybody thought was a crazy

00:26:07.950 --> 00:26:11.880
waste of time led to the most
money I ever made and led to

00:26:11.880 --> 00:26:13.650
the best career I ever had.

00:26:13.650 --> 00:26:16.840
That crazy, playing with doll
impulse led me to a house in

00:26:16.840 --> 00:26:19.970
Los Angeles and raising
two kids.

00:26:19.970 --> 00:26:24.660
So don't discount your secret
love that you might be a

00:26:24.660 --> 00:26:26.390
little bit embarrassed
or ashamed to do.

00:26:26.390 --> 00:26:28.480
I mean, that's part of--
the title of the

00:26:28.480 --> 00:26:30.050
movie comes from that.

00:26:30.050 --> 00:26:33.080
Often, what we love is
a guilty pleasure.

00:26:33.080 --> 00:26:37.110
Or we're afraid to expose our
true, vulnerable self through

00:26:37.110 --> 00:26:38.460
the things we love.

00:26:38.460 --> 00:26:41.830
And we're embarrassed, often, by
the things we love, or the

00:26:41.830 --> 00:26:44.900
things we really want to do.

00:26:44.900 --> 00:26:46.170
But truth is beauty.

00:26:46.170 --> 00:26:48.350
And beauty is embarrassing.

00:26:48.350 --> 00:26:50.370
Don't be embarrassed by it.

00:26:50.370 --> 00:26:53.190
It's kind of like giving you
permission to wear your heart

00:26:53.190 --> 00:26:54.890
on your sleeve.

00:26:54.890 --> 00:26:57.140
And this culture does not want
you to wear your heart on your

00:26:57.140 --> 00:26:58.950
sleeve, especially when
you're young.

00:26:58.950 --> 00:27:02.250
The prototype for the young is,
be wised up and cynical

00:27:02.250 --> 00:27:04.020
and world-weary.

00:27:04.020 --> 00:27:05.060
RYAN GERMICK: What's
up with that--

00:27:05.060 --> 00:27:06.990
WAYNE WHITE: Don't go around so
wide-eyed, you're going to

00:27:06.990 --> 00:27:09.170
get the crap knocked out
of you, you know?

00:27:09.170 --> 00:27:12.840
Build that shell and keep
building layers on that shell.

00:27:12.840 --> 00:27:14.590
Wise up.

00:27:14.590 --> 00:27:17.380
RYAN GERMICK: So like with the
kind of hipster mentality is

00:27:17.380 --> 00:27:19.400
sort of like a very
self-serious--

00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:21.150
kind of the opposite
of punk, in a way.

00:27:21.150 --> 00:27:23.480
WAYNE WHITE: The hipster
mentality is mostly full of

00:27:23.480 --> 00:27:26.470
crap, because they don't
respect the wide-eyed

00:27:26.470 --> 00:27:28.030
enthusiasm of the artist.

00:27:28.030 --> 00:27:31.230
You're supposed to be all
world-weary and depressed.

00:27:31.230 --> 00:27:33.460
And that's supposed to be
a cool thing to do.

00:27:33.460 --> 00:27:35.920
Well, I've been depressed.

00:27:35.920 --> 00:27:39.600
There's nothing cool about
being depressed.

00:27:39.600 --> 00:27:42.790
True depression is a
shameful way to be.

00:27:42.790 --> 00:27:44.900
And it's anti-life.

00:27:44.900 --> 00:27:47.073
But back to your question, who
pulled it all together?

00:27:49.650 --> 00:27:51.250
Paul Reubens pulled
it all together.

00:27:51.250 --> 00:27:53.850
Paul Reubens was our champion.

00:27:53.850 --> 00:27:56.500
He had just come off the movie
"Pee Wee's Big Adventure," Tim

00:27:56.500 --> 00:27:58.040
Burton's first feature.

00:27:58.040 --> 00:27:59.790
And he was hot as a pistol.

00:27:59.790 --> 00:28:05.110
And he had the power that
celebrity can give you.

00:28:05.110 --> 00:28:08.450
And also, he was the rare
combination of a celebrity who

00:28:08.450 --> 00:28:11.020
totally understood art and
the creative spirit.

00:28:11.020 --> 00:28:12.650
And he championed us.

00:28:12.650 --> 00:28:14.580
He protected us from
the network.

00:28:14.580 --> 00:28:17.830
And also, a woman named Judy
Price, who was in charge of

00:28:17.830 --> 00:28:20.950
children's programming,
had the same rebel

00:28:20.950 --> 00:28:22.560
spirit that he did.

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:24.960
And they both protected
us from the network.

00:28:24.960 --> 00:28:27.700
Usually, networks kill
everything with their notes

00:28:27.700 --> 00:28:31.190
and their meddling and their
worrying about making money

00:28:31.190 --> 00:28:31.980
and whatnot.

00:28:31.980 --> 00:28:34.700
But we were in our own
protective bubble.

00:28:34.700 --> 00:28:36.550
And that's the power
of the show.

00:28:36.550 --> 00:28:40.030
It was a downtown New York art
project done by people all new

00:28:40.030 --> 00:28:43.160
to Hollywood, a bunch of
underground cartoonists,

00:28:43.160 --> 00:28:44.610
painters, and sculptors.

00:28:44.610 --> 00:28:47.100
And it just happened to be a New
York art project that got

00:28:47.100 --> 00:28:48.460
on national television.

00:28:48.460 --> 00:28:50.690
And that's exactly its power.

00:28:50.690 --> 00:28:51.800
RYAN GERMICK: Awesome.

00:28:51.800 --> 00:28:52.240
Next slide.

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:53.520
WAYNE WHITE: And, of
course, the genius

00:28:53.520 --> 00:28:55.370
of the Pee Wee character.

00:28:55.370 --> 00:28:56.740
I mean, what a great
character.

00:28:56.740 --> 00:28:59.240
He deserves to be right up there
with Buster Keaton and

00:28:59.240 --> 00:29:01.250
all the greats.

00:29:01.250 --> 00:29:03.280
RYAN GERMICK: So we have a
couple slides of your drawings

00:29:03.280 --> 00:29:05.170
from the time.

00:29:05.170 --> 00:29:07.135
Talk about-- where did
Randy come from?

00:29:07.135 --> 00:29:09.210
WAYNE WHITE: Well, Randy-- all
the characters were already on

00:29:09.210 --> 00:29:10.340
paper when I came along.

00:29:10.340 --> 00:29:14.140
I didn't invent the concepts,
but I did invent the visuals.

00:29:14.140 --> 00:29:19.300
And Randy, of course, is a
classic redheaded bully.

00:29:19.300 --> 00:29:22.590
I was bullied by a redhead
in school.

00:29:22.590 --> 00:29:23.965
And I originally wanted (IN
SOUTHERN ACCENT) Randy to have

00:29:23.965 --> 00:29:26.130
a southern accent.

00:29:26.130 --> 00:29:28.174
But no, they wanted to go with
this classic, (DOING CHARACTER

00:29:28.174 --> 00:29:30.670
VOICE) yeah, kind of Bowery
boys kind of thing.

00:29:30.670 --> 00:29:32.550
So I went with that.

00:29:32.550 --> 00:29:33.660
RYAN GERMICK: You were
also the voice--

00:29:33.660 --> 00:29:34.728
WAYNE WHITE: I was the-- (DOING
CHARACTER VOICE) yeah,

00:29:34.728 --> 00:29:35.564
I was the voice.

00:29:35.564 --> 00:29:38.200
Yeah, smoking's cool,
boys and girls.

00:29:38.200 --> 00:29:45.330
And he's the classic bully that
we've all confronted.

00:29:45.330 --> 00:29:48.260
I mean, one of the classic
redheaded bullies in cinema is

00:29:48.260 --> 00:29:53.800
the kid from "A Christmas
Story." But I

00:29:53.800 --> 00:29:54.840
wasn't thinking of him.

00:29:54.840 --> 00:29:56.610
I was thinking of my own
personal experience.

00:29:56.610 --> 00:29:58.350
But I was delighted to see that

00:29:58.350 --> 00:29:59.640
particular redheaded bully.

00:29:59.640 --> 00:30:02.600
That's another cultural
icon, that kid.

00:30:02.600 --> 00:30:04.530
RYAN GERMICK: What is it about
redheads that makes them such

00:30:04.530 --> 00:30:05.680
bad people?

00:30:05.680 --> 00:30:09.505
WAYNE WHITE: Well, are there
any gingers here today?

00:30:09.505 --> 00:30:11.010
RYAN GERMICK: I'm
just kidding.

00:30:11.010 --> 00:30:12.380
WAYNE WHITE: I don't know.

00:30:12.380 --> 00:30:13.590
It's just-- red.

00:30:13.590 --> 00:30:15.470
You know, seeing red.

00:30:15.470 --> 00:30:19.430
Red is the flag of danger.

00:30:19.430 --> 00:30:20.900
Plus, they have freckles.

00:30:20.900 --> 00:30:25.260
And freckles on a puppet
are always fun to do.

00:30:25.260 --> 00:30:26.390
RYAN GERMICK: We look forward
to the comments on

00:30:26.390 --> 00:30:27.540
the video from that.

00:30:27.540 --> 00:30:30.280
WAYNE WHITE: And Randy also
represents the return to a

00:30:30.280 --> 00:30:33.380
classic puppet look that we
wanted to bring to "Pee Wee's

00:30:33.380 --> 00:30:33.645
Playhouse."

00:30:33.645 --> 00:30:34.110
RYAN GERMICK: It looks--

00:30:34.110 --> 00:30:35.910
Howdy Doody seems like
a reference there.

00:30:35.910 --> 00:30:37.440
WAYNE WHITE: Howdy Doody,
the great Peter

00:30:37.440 --> 00:30:40.230
Baird, the Jerry Mahoney--

00:30:40.230 --> 00:30:42.640
hard surfaces on puppets.

00:30:42.640 --> 00:30:45.730
The Muppets had ruled the roost
for so long with that

00:30:45.730 --> 00:30:49.550
plush toy, felt, and ping-pong
ball aesthetic that everybody

00:30:49.550 --> 00:30:50.710
and their brother had copied.

00:30:50.710 --> 00:30:51.790
I love the Muppets.

00:30:51.790 --> 00:30:53.960
Jim Henson was a great genius.

00:30:53.960 --> 00:30:57.220
But man, they had cornered
the market on puppets.

00:30:57.220 --> 00:31:00.280
And we wanted to bring back a
more classic puppet look.

00:31:00.280 --> 00:31:02.870
And Randy was a classic
example of that.

00:31:02.870 --> 00:31:04.070
RYAN GERMICK: Another
character you

00:31:04.070 --> 00:31:06.430
worked on was Mr. Kite.

00:31:06.430 --> 00:31:07.900
WAYNE WHITE: Yes. (DOING VOICE)
Yes, and I was also the

00:31:07.900 --> 00:31:09.060
voice of Mr. Kite.

00:31:09.060 --> 00:31:12.100
Rain, Pee Wee, rain.

00:31:12.100 --> 00:31:17.720
And of course, at the time, I
was so ambitious and eager, I

00:31:17.720 --> 00:31:19.420
worked harder--

00:31:19.420 --> 00:31:21.595
That's another quality
of mine.

00:31:21.595 --> 00:31:24.070
I was a horrible student.

00:31:24.070 --> 00:31:25.370
I didn't listen to
the teacher.

00:31:25.370 --> 00:31:26.660
I cased the room.

00:31:26.660 --> 00:31:28.240
OK, who's the best
one in here?

00:31:28.240 --> 00:31:29.510
OK, I'm going to beat you.

00:31:29.510 --> 00:31:33.430
It was always a competition
with me in a classroom.

00:31:33.430 --> 00:31:34.535
I wanted to be the best.

00:31:34.535 --> 00:31:37.100
And I wanted to figure out how
to beat everybody else.

00:31:37.100 --> 00:31:39.350
That's what my sports background
has taught me.

00:31:39.350 --> 00:31:41.170
Maybe a little too
competitive.

00:31:41.170 --> 00:31:46.080
And in that spirit of
competition, I did like 50

00:31:46.080 --> 00:31:48.090
pages of drawings
of Mr. Kites.

00:31:48.090 --> 00:31:48.610
RYAN GERMICK: Yeah,
I wondered--

00:31:48.610 --> 00:31:49.160
I saw the numbers.

00:31:49.160 --> 00:31:50.100
It's like 454.

00:31:50.100 --> 00:31:52.080
Are those really sequential?

00:31:52.080 --> 00:31:54.800
WAYNE WHITE: I would go
overboard with the drawing and

00:31:54.800 --> 00:31:57.460
the ideas, making sure that I
was running circles around

00:31:57.460 --> 00:31:59.320
everybody in the room.

00:31:59.320 --> 00:32:02.670
I might not have been the best
drawer or the most talent, but

00:32:02.670 --> 00:32:05.830
I was damn sure going to
be the hardest worker.

00:32:05.830 --> 00:32:09.440
And so I drew the
hell out of--

00:32:09.440 --> 00:32:11.530
and it wound up being the
simplest thing possible, of

00:32:11.530 --> 00:32:13.940
course, after all my ideas.

00:32:13.940 --> 00:32:17.730
And so this is a good example
of the design process.

00:32:17.730 --> 00:32:21.590
But it's also a good example of
my over-reaching attitude.

00:32:21.590 --> 00:32:24.340
And my overworking attitude.

00:32:24.340 --> 00:32:25.650
Which is a good thing to have.

00:32:25.650 --> 00:32:27.310
I mean, that's another thing.

00:32:27.310 --> 00:32:29.290
If you're not the most talented
in the room, make

00:32:29.290 --> 00:32:31.330
sure you're the hardest
working in the room.

00:32:31.330 --> 00:32:33.740
It'll get you somewhere.

00:32:33.740 --> 00:32:37.510
RYAN GERMICK: Next over there is
a clip from the movie, that

00:32:37.510 --> 00:32:40.260
I kind of cut up about "Pee
Wee." Let's check it out.

00:32:40.260 --> 00:32:41.655
That was great.

00:32:45.080 --> 00:32:46.060
RYAN GERMICK: I would
like that DVD.

00:32:46.060 --> 00:32:48.380
Of the Pee Wee Herman that no
one ever saw. "Pee Wee" show.

00:32:48.380 --> 00:32:50.015
WAYNE WHITE: Well, hopefully
it's going to be on the extras

00:32:50.015 --> 00:32:52.180
on the DVD that comes
out in February.

00:32:52.180 --> 00:32:53.500
For the movie.

00:32:53.500 --> 00:32:54.760
RYAN GERMICK: Awesome.

00:32:54.760 --> 00:32:57.250
So this is one of the
word paintings.

00:32:57.250 --> 00:33:02.500
So to summarize, I guess, you
had a really successful run in

00:33:02.500 --> 00:33:04.950
Hollywood with "Pee Wee" and
"Beakman's World" and a bunch

00:33:04.950 --> 00:33:07.510
of other shows.

00:33:07.510 --> 00:33:09.910
And then you kind
of burnt out.

00:33:09.910 --> 00:33:10.410
Fair to say?

00:33:10.410 --> 00:33:11.430
WAYNE WHITE: Yes.

00:33:11.430 --> 00:33:13.180
The typical Hollywood story.

00:33:13.180 --> 00:33:15.470
I was overworked.

00:33:15.470 --> 00:33:20.160
I was over-saturated with doing
kid shows and puppets.

00:33:20.160 --> 00:33:23.520
I was typed as the wacky
kid show guy.

00:33:23.520 --> 00:33:27.330
And I just needed a
break from it all.

00:33:27.330 --> 00:33:29.880
That's where my depression
came in.

00:33:29.880 --> 00:33:32.480
I was exhausted physically.

00:33:32.480 --> 00:33:36.300
And, like I said, that thing
about working harder than

00:33:36.300 --> 00:33:39.590
anybody in the room, it
has its liabilities.

00:33:39.590 --> 00:33:42.280
And I literally worked
myself into a rut.

00:33:42.280 --> 00:33:43.050
Into a hole.

00:33:43.050 --> 00:33:44.990
And I had to get out
of that hole.

00:33:44.990 --> 00:33:47.470
And so I thought I would
return to painting.

00:33:47.470 --> 00:33:52.450
But I wanted to do a 180 from
this cartoon expressionism.

00:33:52.450 --> 00:33:55.880
And I wanted to not return to
the abstract expressionism I

00:33:55.880 --> 00:33:58.340
was taught in undergraduate
school.

00:33:58.340 --> 00:34:00.620
So I taught myself traditional
painting techniques.

00:34:00.620 --> 00:34:03.337
I started looking at Winslow
Homer and Thomas Eakins and

00:34:03.337 --> 00:34:05.210
the Hudson River
Valley school.

00:34:05.210 --> 00:34:07.200
I bought a book about
how to paint

00:34:07.200 --> 00:34:09.130
traditional oil paintings.

00:34:09.130 --> 00:34:11.610
And I started doing these
history paintings.

00:34:11.610 --> 00:34:14.300
Again, hearkening back to my
Chattanooga childhood--

00:34:14.300 --> 00:34:17.760
the Civil War, the
Cherokee Indians.

00:34:17.760 --> 00:34:19.550
The scenic beauty
of the place.

00:34:19.550 --> 00:34:21.860
And I was doing these very
traditional kind of history

00:34:21.860 --> 00:34:25.290
paintings with kind of
weird psychological

00:34:25.290 --> 00:34:26.989
undertones to them.

00:34:26.989 --> 00:34:30.580
And I was buying thrift store
paintings just for the frames.

00:34:30.580 --> 00:34:35.360
And the paintings started
getting a little more surreal,

00:34:35.360 --> 00:34:38.000
but they were still
traditionally painted.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:39.659
And I thought one day,
I'm going to put

00:34:39.659 --> 00:34:41.040
words into the painting.

00:34:41.040 --> 00:34:42.500
Into a landscape.

00:34:42.500 --> 00:34:45.150
And I picked out one
of the thrift store

00:34:45.150 --> 00:34:47.210
landscapes for the frame.

00:34:47.210 --> 00:34:50.560
And right before I kicked the
cheap reproduction out, I

00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:53.400
thought, what about if I just
painted on the landscape that

00:34:53.400 --> 00:34:55.100
was already in there.

00:34:55.100 --> 00:34:57.878
It would save a lot of time.

00:34:57.878 --> 00:35:05.410
And so on a moment's whim,
sponta-- spontane--

00:35:05.410 --> 00:35:07.586
I can't say words today.

00:35:07.586 --> 00:35:11.640
Spontaneously, I painted the
words into the already

00:35:11.640 --> 00:35:14.380
pre-existing cheap landscape
reproduction.

00:35:14.380 --> 00:35:17.670
And thus was born a series that
I call "word paintings."

00:35:17.670 --> 00:35:20.200
And maybe that's how you
first knew of me.

00:35:20.200 --> 00:35:25.480
That's certainly my most
notorious body of work.

00:35:25.480 --> 00:35:28.400
And it's how I got into
the fine arts world.

00:35:28.400 --> 00:35:30.310
I'm still painting them today.

00:35:30.310 --> 00:35:32.560
RYAN GERMICK: I want to just
give you a shout-out, because

00:35:32.560 --> 00:35:35.186
there's some really beautiful
technical stuff going on with

00:35:35.186 --> 00:35:35.460
the paintings.

00:35:35.460 --> 00:35:38.250
The lighting on the letters and
the ripples in the water.

00:35:38.250 --> 00:35:39.380
It's really well done.

00:35:39.380 --> 00:35:40.350
WAYNE WHITE: Thank you.

00:35:40.350 --> 00:35:43.560
That was from the years of
self-study of oil painting

00:35:43.560 --> 00:35:44.470
techniques.

00:35:44.470 --> 00:35:50.330
And doing traditional type
of rendering it in paint.

00:35:50.330 --> 00:35:52.340
These are in acrylic,
but acrylic is

00:35:52.340 --> 00:35:55.870
just fake oil paint.

00:35:55.870 --> 00:35:58.110
And I only use landscape
reproductions.

00:35:58.110 --> 00:35:59.630
I don't paint on originals.

00:35:59.630 --> 00:36:02.140
Originals have too much of
a human smell on them.

00:36:02.140 --> 00:36:05.420
Plus, that would be an act of
defacement, because then that

00:36:05.420 --> 00:36:07.350
original is gone forever.

00:36:07.350 --> 00:36:10.140
These reproductions are just
empty commodities.

00:36:10.140 --> 00:36:13.180
There's thousands, maybe even
millions, of these things.

00:36:13.180 --> 00:36:14.880
And they're like
an empty stage.

00:36:14.880 --> 00:36:16.220
There's no real art there.

00:36:16.220 --> 00:36:18.140
There's no human presence.

00:36:18.140 --> 00:36:22.170
But they are a beautiful setting
for these words.

00:36:22.170 --> 00:36:24.350
And I don't think of
them as defacement.

00:36:24.350 --> 00:36:27.290
I think of them as collaboration
with the artist.

00:36:27.290 --> 00:36:31.200
Because I respect his color
palette, his sense of light.

00:36:31.200 --> 00:36:32.200
The environmental--

00:36:32.200 --> 00:36:34.730
I try to get the shadows and
everything just right.

00:36:34.730 --> 00:36:36.790
So it's a bit of a collaboration
with these

00:36:36.790 --> 00:36:40.430
long-dead masters of this
sofa art genre.

00:36:40.430 --> 00:36:43.430
And of course, I discovered--

00:36:43.430 --> 00:36:46.850
what began as just a jokey
gesture deepened as I started

00:36:46.850 --> 00:36:48.130
to look at it.

00:36:48.130 --> 00:36:49.590
It references so many things--

00:36:49.590 --> 00:36:54.160
Americana, the sense
of the past.

00:36:54.160 --> 00:36:57.630
It's using these objects that
everybody can relate to.

00:36:57.630 --> 00:37:00.090
They've all seen these paintings
at granny's house or

00:37:00.090 --> 00:37:01.240
in their own house.

00:37:01.240 --> 00:37:02.490
Or at the dentist's office.

00:37:02.490 --> 00:37:06.110
They're a ubiquitous part of
American culture, these

00:37:06.110 --> 00:37:08.230
prevalent, kitschy things.

00:37:08.230 --> 00:37:10.240
So there's that reference
point.

00:37:10.240 --> 00:37:12.330
There's art history
references.

00:37:12.330 --> 00:37:15.060
And of course, there's the layer
of humor I bring to it.

00:37:15.060 --> 00:37:18.000
So they were very resonant in a
way that I never planned in

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:19.210
a million years.

00:37:19.210 --> 00:37:21.590
And I think a lot of the
best discoveries and

00:37:21.590 --> 00:37:24.340
ideas happen that way.

00:37:24.340 --> 00:37:27.480
They just kind of bubble up
from your subconscious.

00:37:27.480 --> 00:37:32.660
And you can't pre-plan art.

00:37:32.660 --> 00:37:34.500
It's being in the moment.

00:37:34.500 --> 00:37:37.360
The creative act is not
an act of analysis.

00:37:37.360 --> 00:37:41.400
It's just listening to some
weird gut-- or some weird

00:37:41.400 --> 00:37:43.130
voice inside of yourself.

00:37:43.130 --> 00:37:46.460
And these are a testament
to that.

00:37:46.460 --> 00:37:48.766
RYAN GERMICK: I think we have
a couple more to check out.

00:37:48.766 --> 00:37:49.500
WAYNE WHITE: Yes.

00:37:49.500 --> 00:37:53.410
This one's called "Just a
Picture/ Shunned by Scholars/

00:37:53.410 --> 00:38:00.710
Now it Costs $10,000." And
that's my tribute to the old

00:38:00.710 --> 00:38:02.860
Burma-Shave signs.

00:38:02.860 --> 00:38:04.880
I'm sure a lot of you don't--

00:38:04.880 --> 00:38:06.160
ever heard of that.

00:38:06.160 --> 00:38:08.050
But people of a certain age--

00:38:08.050 --> 00:38:09.940
I'm a little too young, even.

00:38:09.940 --> 00:38:13.060
But in the early '50s, there was
a series of advertisements

00:38:13.060 --> 00:38:15.500
by the side of the road,
rhyming signs--

00:38:15.500 --> 00:38:18.290
like every 50 yards would to
be a sign and they rhymed.

00:38:18.290 --> 00:38:21.360
And then the payoff would
be, Burma Shave!

00:38:21.360 --> 00:38:23.930
It was a nice little piece
of sequential art by

00:38:23.930 --> 00:38:24.640
the side of the road.

00:38:24.640 --> 00:38:25.810
And I always loved that.

00:38:25.810 --> 00:38:28.400
And we had our own versions of
it down in Chattanooga with

00:38:28.400 --> 00:38:31.320
tourist traps, especially the
Georgia Game Park. "See

00:38:31.320 --> 00:38:33.120
three-headed dog." "See
blah blah blah."

00:38:33.120 --> 00:38:34.130
But it didn't rhyme.

00:38:34.130 --> 00:38:37.080
This is a direct reference to
the Burma Shave campaigns.

00:38:37.080 --> 00:38:42.400
And I'm a big fan of roadside
attractions and Americana.

00:38:42.400 --> 00:38:45.430
And early motels and
advertising.

00:38:45.430 --> 00:38:49.240
And anything that has to do with
roadside America, I love.

00:38:49.240 --> 00:38:52.670
And it's, of course, a sly
dig at the pretensions of

00:38:52.670 --> 00:38:55.810
high and low art.

00:38:55.810 --> 00:38:58.740
I don't know if it's
sly or not.

00:38:58.740 --> 00:39:01.240
RYAN GERMICK: This one--

00:39:01.240 --> 00:39:04.250
WAYNE WHITE: This is a series
of works I did where I would

00:39:04.250 --> 00:39:09.550
pour paint on the picture, let
it puddle and dry, and then I

00:39:09.550 --> 00:39:10.280
would look at it.

00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:13.170
Then I would tell you
what it looks like.

00:39:13.170 --> 00:39:16.780
To me, that looked like the
profile of Norman Rockwell.

00:39:16.780 --> 00:39:17.680
RYAN GERMICK: I can see that.

00:39:17.680 --> 00:39:19.250
The long neck, kind of
like turtle head.

00:39:19.250 --> 00:39:19.860
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah.

00:39:19.860 --> 00:39:22.650
You know, we've all seen those
pictures of him leaning over

00:39:22.650 --> 00:39:24.650
with a pipe in his
mouth painting.

00:39:24.650 --> 00:39:28.140
See the nose and the
big cranium.

00:39:28.140 --> 00:39:30.120
And I did five or
six of those.

00:39:30.120 --> 00:39:31.320
Didn't sell a one.

00:39:31.320 --> 00:39:33.060
Nobody liked these.

00:39:33.060 --> 00:39:33.750
I love them.

00:39:33.750 --> 00:39:37.670
Again, it's commenting on the
pretensions of art and how

00:39:37.670 --> 00:39:39.220
people really look at art.

00:39:39.220 --> 00:39:40.830
None of us--

00:39:40.830 --> 00:39:42.200
come on, admit it.

00:39:42.200 --> 00:39:44.020
You look at an abstract painting
and after a while,

00:39:44.020 --> 00:39:47.401
you start going, hey, that
looks like a dog.

00:39:47.401 --> 00:39:49.800
And it's about cloud gazing.

00:39:49.800 --> 00:39:51.470
We all love to find shapes.

00:39:51.470 --> 00:39:54.960
We all love to impose our
meaning on the world, a world

00:39:54.960 --> 00:40:00.020
that's really scientifically
chaotic, indifferent, and

00:40:00.020 --> 00:40:01.710
couldn't care if we
lived or died.

00:40:01.710 --> 00:40:05.640
Yet, we want to impose our human
qualities on that world.

00:40:05.640 --> 00:40:08.750
We're constantly trying to find
narrative and meaning in

00:40:08.750 --> 00:40:11.500
accidents and chaos
and in nature.

00:40:11.500 --> 00:40:16.100
And that's what that's
reflective on, both our

00:40:16.100 --> 00:40:18.610
instinctive view of
the world and the

00:40:18.610 --> 00:40:20.230
pretensions of high art.

00:40:20.230 --> 00:40:21.500
And it's funny, I think.

00:40:24.900 --> 00:40:26.860
WAYNE WHITE: Yes. "The Most
Expensive Painting in the

00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:30.540
World." Hyperbole is funny.

00:40:30.540 --> 00:40:32.440
That painting, too,
is about that big.

00:40:35.220 --> 00:40:36.080
RYAN GERMICK: It should
be encased behind

00:40:36.080 --> 00:40:36.590
like six inches of--

00:40:36.590 --> 00:40:37.720
WAYNE WHITE: Yes, like
the Mona Lisa.

00:40:37.720 --> 00:40:38.340
RYAN GERMICK: --bullet-proof
glass.

00:40:38.340 --> 00:40:39.760
WAYNE WHITE: Absolutely.

00:40:39.760 --> 00:40:42.460
So that's, again, just
a pot shot at the

00:40:42.460 --> 00:40:43.910
pretensions of the world.

00:40:43.910 --> 00:40:47.190
The insane economy of art.

00:40:47.190 --> 00:40:50.880
The insane way things
accrue value.

00:40:50.880 --> 00:40:51.920
You know.

00:40:51.920 --> 00:40:52.245
RYAN GERMICK: Yeah.

00:40:52.245 --> 00:40:54.930
I mean, back to my
plasma-cutting pizza

00:40:54.930 --> 00:40:56.080
experience.

00:40:56.080 --> 00:40:58.320
It also became clear to me
pretty early on living in New

00:40:58.320 --> 00:41:03.920
York as a Midwestern teenager
that the gallery art system is

00:41:03.920 --> 00:41:07.010
no less ridiculous than
shlubbing to the Village Voice

00:41:07.010 --> 00:41:09.250
to drop off your editorial
illustration portfolio.

00:41:09.250 --> 00:41:10.120
WAYNE WHITE: Yes.

00:41:10.120 --> 00:41:12.280
And again, it's all
about being--

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:14.770
the art world is fashion.

00:41:14.770 --> 00:41:17.450
And we all know how
absurd fashion is.

00:41:17.450 --> 00:41:19.470
I mean, if you look to "The
New York Times" fashion

00:41:19.470 --> 00:41:22.190
supplement magazine, it's
the most ridiculous

00:41:22.190 --> 00:41:23.250
thing in the world.

00:41:23.250 --> 00:41:25.150
Who wears those fashions?

00:41:25.150 --> 00:41:25.770
Nobody does.

00:41:25.770 --> 00:41:27.630
I don't understand fashion.

00:41:27.630 --> 00:41:33.660
These men strutting down the
catwalk wearing, like, Speedos

00:41:33.660 --> 00:41:35.240
with a fur jacket.

00:41:35.240 --> 00:41:36.670
And they're taking
it seriously.

00:41:36.670 --> 00:41:38.840
It's all done with
a straight face.

00:41:38.840 --> 00:41:43.330
And it's so offensive to human
nature, fashion is.

00:41:43.330 --> 00:41:45.490
I have another painting, it's
called "Good-looking People

00:41:45.490 --> 00:41:48.530
Having Fun Without You." That's
the number one message

00:41:48.530 --> 00:41:49.960
of the media.

00:41:49.960 --> 00:41:52.880
That's the number one message
of the media.

00:41:52.880 --> 00:41:54.300
Look what you missed.

00:41:54.300 --> 00:41:56.360
Look what you are missing
out on, loser.

00:41:56.360 --> 00:41:59.110
You better buy this watch or
these shoes or this jacket to

00:41:59.110 --> 00:42:01.430
get in on the party that
you're missing out on.

00:42:01.430 --> 00:42:03.680
And you never find that
party your whole life.

00:42:03.680 --> 00:42:06.780
Even the people at the party
aren't at that party.

00:42:09.310 --> 00:42:13.130
There's this mythic,
unattainable, super sexy,

00:42:13.130 --> 00:42:17.280
super cool ideal that capitalist
culture creates and

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:19.530
drives us forward by our nose.

00:42:19.530 --> 00:42:21.280
And it's bullshit.

00:42:21.280 --> 00:42:22.810
And we live our lives with this

00:42:22.810 --> 00:42:26.350
insecurity because of that.

00:42:26.350 --> 00:42:31.750
And I think that's a sacred
mission, is to knock down

00:42:31.750 --> 00:42:33.080
those false idols.

00:42:33.080 --> 00:42:35.790
The emperor's new clothes
kind of thing.

00:42:35.790 --> 00:42:38.600
To break through that and unite
us in the fact that

00:42:38.600 --> 00:42:42.410
we're all just these vulnerable
creatures.

00:42:42.410 --> 00:42:47.760
And that's just crap just to get
you to spend your money.

00:42:47.760 --> 00:42:49.210
RYAN GERMICK: I am with you.

00:42:49.210 --> 00:42:51.800
But I saw the show that was at
the San Francisco de Young

00:42:51.800 --> 00:42:54.490
Museum recently for Jean
Paul Gaultier.

00:42:54.490 --> 00:42:55.850
That guy's pretty on point.

00:42:55.850 --> 00:42:58.250
WAYNE WHITE: Well, you know what
There's geniuses in the

00:42:58.250 --> 00:42:58.870
fashion world.

00:42:58.870 --> 00:43:02.180
Again, I take these polemical
points and it sounds--

00:43:02.180 --> 00:43:04.770
I do that for the rhetoric
and the passion.

00:43:04.770 --> 00:43:07.950
And to reach out on an
emotional level.

00:43:07.950 --> 00:43:10.430
But everything is super
complicated.

00:43:10.430 --> 00:43:12.590
I can't hit on all the points.

00:43:12.590 --> 00:43:14.750
I just have rhetoric.

00:43:14.750 --> 00:43:22.980
But fashion is an ingenious,
fascinating visual form.

00:43:22.980 --> 00:43:26.690
And there's elegance
and beauty to it.

00:43:26.690 --> 00:43:27.700
RYAN GERMICK: And even
humor sometimes.

00:43:27.700 --> 00:43:28.450
WAYNE WHITE: And humor.

00:43:28.450 --> 00:43:28.780
There's everything there.

00:43:28.780 --> 00:43:30.310
RYAN GERMICK: But most of the
time it's pretty ridiculous.

00:43:30.310 --> 00:43:34.120
WAYNE WHITE: But it's really in
the hands of money makers.

00:43:34.120 --> 00:43:36.960
I'm not belittling any fashion
designer or anybody who's

00:43:36.960 --> 00:43:39.640
interested in it, but it gets
in the hands of the money

00:43:39.640 --> 00:43:40.900
makers and they ruin it.

00:43:40.900 --> 00:43:44.390
Money makers always
ruin everything.

00:43:44.390 --> 00:43:46.140
But we all gotta
make money too.

00:43:46.140 --> 00:43:48.290
Again, another, like--

00:43:48.290 --> 00:43:52.040
you can't take any position in
this world without it having a

00:43:52.040 --> 00:43:54.440
direct opposite.

00:43:54.440 --> 00:43:56.820
I'm finding that out as I go
around and become more of a

00:43:56.820 --> 00:43:57.730
public speaker.

00:43:57.730 --> 00:44:00.410
I'm often caught up in the heat
of my rhetoric, and I'm

00:44:00.410 --> 00:44:03.320
thinking, you know, somebody
could debate me down to the

00:44:03.320 --> 00:44:04.350
ground on this.

00:44:04.350 --> 00:44:07.560
But I'm trying to hit these
emotional points that we all

00:44:07.560 --> 00:44:08.690
can relate to.

00:44:08.690 --> 00:44:09.866
RYAN GERMICK: Yeah.

00:44:09.866 --> 00:44:11.600
What do we got-- what's
our next one?

00:44:11.600 --> 00:44:13.040
So it looks like--

00:44:13.040 --> 00:44:13.785
WAYNE WHITE: It got crazy.

00:44:13.785 --> 00:44:14.670
RYAN GERMICK: It got crazy.

00:44:14.670 --> 00:44:15.150
WAYNE WHITE: Yeah.

00:44:15.150 --> 00:44:18.070
I got tired of the straight
ahead text.

00:44:18.070 --> 00:44:21.325
I simply wanted to do
variations, and see how far I

00:44:21.325 --> 00:44:22.160
could push it.

00:44:22.160 --> 00:44:26.320
These are words made out of
a cartoon Western town.

00:44:26.320 --> 00:44:29.380
You know, why not?

00:44:29.380 --> 00:44:32.790
And it literally says, "all
an act." There's an A

00:44:32.790 --> 00:44:34.340
laying on its side.

00:44:34.340 --> 00:44:38.550
There's an L, another L, an A,
the C reaching up into the

00:44:38.550 --> 00:44:41.320
buggy, and then the last T.

00:44:41.320 --> 00:44:44.020
And I was literally trying to
push the idea of typography as

00:44:44.020 --> 00:44:45.250
far as I could go.

00:44:45.250 --> 00:44:48.960
And take the street, a Western
cartoon-like tourist town

00:44:48.960 --> 00:44:52.690
street that you'd see, you
know, in a comic book.

00:44:52.690 --> 00:44:56.340
And use those as the post and
lintels of typography.

00:44:56.340 --> 00:44:57.176
RYAN GERMICK: Yeah.

00:44:57.176 --> 00:44:58.430
Cool.

00:44:58.430 --> 00:45:02.300
So I just keep trying to
push the limits and the

00:45:02.300 --> 00:45:03.940
possibilities of typography.

00:45:03.940 --> 00:45:07.110
I think typography is
a great art form.

00:45:07.110 --> 00:45:09.710
And worthy of--

00:45:09.710 --> 00:45:10.820
I'm sure a lot of you--

00:45:10.820 --> 00:45:12.780
of course, Google is
built on the--

00:45:12.780 --> 00:45:15.440
a lot of the Google image
is about typography.

00:45:15.440 --> 00:45:18.353
It's an incredible topic,
inexhaustible.

00:45:23.360 --> 00:45:26.060
RYAN GERMICK: This is now
actually a physical object.

00:45:26.060 --> 00:45:27.560
WAYNE WHITE: It's an
aluminum cut-out.

00:45:27.560 --> 00:45:31.670
Laser-cut aluminum that
floats about two

00:45:31.670 --> 00:45:32.740
inches from the wall.

00:45:32.740 --> 00:45:36.170
It says, "let's have a smirking
contest." That's

00:45:36.170 --> 00:45:38.850
another condition of society.

00:45:38.850 --> 00:45:41.800
You were talking about earlier
with hipsters.

00:45:41.800 --> 00:45:44.500
It seems like the default
position of our

00:45:44.500 --> 00:45:47.130
society is the smirk.

00:45:47.130 --> 00:45:50.130
If you're smirking,
you're cool, man.

00:45:50.130 --> 00:45:52.030
You're ready for all comers.

00:45:52.030 --> 00:45:53.910
You got your guard up.

00:45:53.910 --> 00:45:55.960
Everything's bullshit.

00:45:55.960 --> 00:45:57.560
I'm going to smirk
about everything.

00:45:57.560 --> 00:45:58.040
I'm cool.

00:45:58.040 --> 00:46:00.560
I'm too cool to believe
in anything.

00:46:00.560 --> 00:46:03.870
Nihilism seems to be the
default position of our

00:46:03.870 --> 00:46:05.640
society in so many ways.

00:46:05.640 --> 00:46:09.030
And the intellectual challenges
seem to be who can

00:46:09.030 --> 00:46:09.980
be the smirkiest.

00:46:09.980 --> 00:46:12.230
Or who can be the most
disbelieving.

00:46:12.230 --> 00:46:14.360
Who can cut each
other the most.

00:46:18.300 --> 00:46:20.400
It's a cruel world.

00:46:20.400 --> 00:46:23.076
And why?

00:46:23.076 --> 00:46:26.040
Why?

00:46:26.040 --> 00:46:29.460
But it's also funny too. "Let's
have a smirk--" that

00:46:29.460 --> 00:46:31.230
seems to boil it all down.

00:46:31.230 --> 00:46:36.140
When two hipsters meet, it's
a smirking contest.

00:46:36.140 --> 00:46:39.730
But on a technical, visual
level, this reflects my love

00:46:39.730 --> 00:46:42.040
of sculpture and objecthood.

00:46:42.040 --> 00:46:45.920
And literally taking the words
out of the context and making

00:46:45.920 --> 00:46:48.110
them a sculptural object.

00:46:48.110 --> 00:46:49.430
And I love painted metal.

00:46:49.430 --> 00:46:50.990
This is like painted aluminum.

00:46:50.990 --> 00:46:52.310
Acrylic on aluminum.

00:46:52.310 --> 00:46:52.960
RYAN GERMICK: So I
