00:47:39.070 --> 00:47:39.960
WAYNE WHITE: Hi, Julie.

00:47:39.960 --> 00:47:44.140
JULIE: And I want to know, how
did Neil find you or decide to

00:47:44.140 --> 00:47:46.520
make a documentary about you?

00:47:46.520 --> 00:47:48.900
WAYNE WHITE: Well, I met Neil
12 years ago, when he was a

00:47:48.900 --> 00:47:51.230
young punk right out
of Oklahoma.

00:47:51.230 --> 00:47:54.570
He was an unpaid intern at this
design company where I

00:47:54.570 --> 00:47:55.730
was working.

00:47:55.730 --> 00:48:00.450
And I paid no attention
to him at all.

00:48:00.450 --> 00:48:02.060
I just thought, please,
get away--

00:48:02.060 --> 00:48:04.040
give me a sandwich, you know?

00:48:04.040 --> 00:48:07.430
And 12 years later, he
owns that company.

00:48:07.430 --> 00:48:08.390
That's his company now.

00:48:08.390 --> 00:48:11.610
That's the kind of
guy Neil is.

00:48:11.610 --> 00:48:14.870
But three years ago, when my
book came out, that was edited

00:48:14.870 --> 00:48:19.700
and produced by Todd Oldham,
he got together with me and

00:48:19.700 --> 00:48:21.320
said, hey, you're hot
property now, man.

00:48:21.320 --> 00:48:22.520
You've got this book.

00:48:22.520 --> 00:48:24.270
You're in Esquire magazine.

00:48:24.270 --> 00:48:25.900
Let's do a short film.

00:48:25.900 --> 00:48:30.250
And that short film grew
into a feature film.

00:48:30.250 --> 00:48:32.780
And here we are three
years later.

00:48:32.780 --> 00:48:35.370
So that's how I met Neil.

00:48:35.370 --> 00:48:38.570
And three years ago, I really
didn't know him still.

00:48:38.570 --> 00:48:40.810
I thought of him as that young
kid from Oklahoma.

00:48:40.810 --> 00:48:43.260
And our friendship grew
as this movie grew.

00:48:43.260 --> 00:48:46.060
And the movie grew organically
out of our friendship.

00:48:46.060 --> 00:48:48.420
I think that's one of the
powers of the movie.

00:48:48.420 --> 00:48:50.080
There was no set agenda.

00:48:50.080 --> 00:48:53.210
There was no M.O. There was
no outline, no script--

00:48:53.210 --> 00:48:53.890
nothing.

00:48:53.890 --> 00:48:55.740
We just kind of played
it by ear.

00:48:55.740 --> 00:48:58.980
And it reflects our growing
familiarity with each other.

00:48:58.980 --> 00:49:01.830
And his discovery of me.

00:49:01.830 --> 00:49:06.550
Plus, like a lot of people in
their '30s, my work had a big

00:49:06.550 --> 00:49:08.670
influence on him , through
"Pee Wee's Playhouse,"

00:49:08.670 --> 00:49:10.797
"Beakman's World," the Smashing
Pumpkins video, et

00:49:10.797 --> 00:49:12.170
cetera, et cetera.

00:49:12.170 --> 00:49:15.480
So he was naturally curious
because I had this famous

00:49:15.480 --> 00:49:18.190
stuff I did, but our
friendship was

00:49:18.190 --> 00:49:19.540
reflected in that.

00:49:19.540 --> 00:49:21.594
And my personal life came
out through him.

00:49:21.594 --> 00:49:23.470
JULIE: That's awesome.

00:49:23.470 --> 00:49:26.540
Elaine, his sister, is one
of my best friends.

00:49:26.540 --> 00:49:28.750
So she wanted me to tell you
that she says you have

00:49:28.750 --> 00:49:29.800
