AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:51:08.390 --> 00:51:09.420
WAYNE WHITE: Hi.

00:51:09.420 --> 00:51:10.530
AUDIENCE: I have a question
about the

00:51:10.530 --> 00:51:12.850
Smashing Pumpkins video.

00:51:12.850 --> 00:51:16.670
How did you decide on the
creative direction for that?

00:51:16.670 --> 00:51:18.760
WAYNE WHITE: Well, the concept
again, just like "Pee Wee,"

00:51:18.760 --> 00:51:21.250
was already on paper
when I came along.

00:51:21.250 --> 00:51:24.050
They had that new album,
"Melancholy and the Infinite

00:51:24.050 --> 00:51:28.000
Sadness." And the graphics on
the album were very Victorian

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:29.050
and antique.

00:51:29.050 --> 00:51:32.860
So they wanted something
appropriately antique and 19th

00:51:32.860 --> 00:51:34.580
century for the look.

00:51:34.580 --> 00:51:38.320
And they hit upon the idea of
George Melies' film "A Trip to

00:51:38.320 --> 00:51:41.380
the Moon." So that was
already on paper.

00:51:41.380 --> 00:51:45.100
And the directors, Jonathan
Dayton and Valerie Faris.

00:51:45.100 --> 00:51:46.630
Were friends of mine.

00:51:46.630 --> 00:51:48.210
We'd always wanted
to work together.

00:51:48.210 --> 00:51:50.220
And they were familiar with the
history paintings I had

00:51:50.220 --> 00:51:51.110
been doing.

00:51:51.110 --> 00:51:53.260
I hadn't really started the
word paintings yet.

00:51:53.260 --> 00:51:58.570
So they knew I had a love of
19th century techniques and

00:51:58.570 --> 00:52:02.490
that whole antiquated
kind of look.

00:52:02.490 --> 00:52:07.550
And I love history, I'm a
big student of history.

00:52:07.550 --> 00:52:08.730
And I loved Melies.

00:52:08.730 --> 00:52:11.670
I already had a big picture book
of his that I pored over

00:52:11.670 --> 00:52:12.620
constantly.

00:52:12.620 --> 00:52:14.880
So it was a happy coincidence
that I could get

00:52:14.880 --> 00:52:17.490
together and do that.

00:52:17.490 --> 00:52:20.070
Again, and then I went crazy
on the concept and did a

00:52:20.070 --> 00:52:23.270
million versions
of every scene.

00:52:23.270 --> 00:52:25.120
So that's how that was born.

00:52:25.120 --> 00:52:26.560
AUDIENCE: Were you helping
to actually build the

00:52:26.560 --> 00:52:27.530
